[1] Congo
Date: Sun 16 June 2002, 05:05 GMT 06:05 UK
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: BBC On line [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/hi/english/world/africa/newsid_2047000/2047748.stm>

Meningitis in Congo kills 24
-------------------
The authorities in the Democratic Republic of Congo say at least 24 people
have died in an outbreak of meningitis in the northeast of the country.
The Health Minister, Mashako Mamba, said the illness had struck people
living around Mai-Ndombe lake, about 450 kilometers from the capital,
Kinshasa. He said the illness was spreading quickly as people were wasting
time visiting sorcerers rather than doctors. The Congolese minister also
said extra medical teams had already been sent to the worst affected areas.
[The number of cases of infection in this outbreak is not reported nor is
the serotype of _N. meningitidis_ stated. If case fatality rates are
similar to the Burkina Faso outbreak below, about 250 cases may have
occurred. In an epidemic setting, large-scale immunization is often used
with antimicrobial prophylaxis in closed settings and/or household
contacts. It is not clear if the "sorcerers" were being used to attempt to
treat already-ill individuals or to prevent disease in individuals not yet
sick. - Mod.LL]
